questions.statement:
Given below are two statements one is labelled as Assertion (A) and the other is labelled as &lt;strong&gt;Reason (R).&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;Assertion (A):&lt;/strong&gt; Quantitative research has been subjected to many criticism by qualitative researchers.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;Reason (R):&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;A natural science model is not appropriate for studying the social world.&lt;br /&gt;
In the light of the above statements, choose the most appropriate answer from the options given below:

questions.explanation:
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The correct answer is - &lt;u&gt;Both (A) and (R) are correct and (R) is the correct explanation of (A)&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt; &lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle; font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;/span&gt; &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Assertion (A): Quantitative research criticism&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Quantitative research methods, which rely on &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;numerical and statistical data&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;, have been criticized for their inability to capture the &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;depth and complexity&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; of social phenomena.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Qualitative researchers argue that quantitative methods often ignore the &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;subjective experiences and meanings&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; individuals attach to their actions.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Reason (R): Inappropriateness of natural science models&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Natural science models, such as those used in physics or biology, focus on &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;objectivity, causality, and predictability&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;However, social phenomena are &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;context-dependent&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; and influenced by human emotions, values, and meanings, making such models less suitable.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Correct Explanation&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Both the assertion and reason are correct, and the reason directly explains the criticism raised by qualitative researchers against quantitative methods.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The reliance on natural science models in quantitative research is seen as a major limitation when studying the &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;social world&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt; &lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle; font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;/span&gt; &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Quantitative Research&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Focuses on &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;measurable data&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; and uses structured methods like surveys, experiments, and statistical analysis.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Strengths include &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;generalizability&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; and the ability to test hypotheses.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Limitations include its inability to capture the &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;subjective, interpretive, and contextual dimensions&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; of social realities.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Qualitative Research&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Focuses on &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;understanding meanings&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;, experiences, and narratives through unstructured methods like interviews, focus groups, and observations.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Emphasizes the &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;subjective and interpretive&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; aspects of social phenomena.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Social World and Natural Science Models&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The social world is characterized by &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;human interactions, culture, and emotions&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;, which are dynamic and context-specific.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Natural science models, by contrast, aim to establish &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;universal laws&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; through controlled, objective methods, making them less adaptable to studying &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;complex social realities&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The correct answer is - &lt;u&gt;External validity&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt; &lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle; font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;/span&gt; &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;External validity&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Refers to the extent to which the &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;findings of a study&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; can be applied or generalized to &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;other populations, settings, or times&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It ensures that the conclusions drawn from the research are &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;relevant&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; beyond the specific context in which the study was conducted.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;For example, if a study is conducted on a small group of people, external validity evaluates whether the results can be generalized to a &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;larger or different population&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is a critical aspect of research design, especially in fields like psychology, medicine, and social sciences.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt; &lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle; font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;/span&gt; &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Internal validity&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Focuses on whether the study&amp;#39;s &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;results&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; are due to the variables being tested and not due to other factors.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It measures how well a study was conducted and whether it avoids &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;confounding variables&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Reliability&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Refers to the &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;consistency&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; of the results when a study is repeated under the same conditions.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;A reliable study produces &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;similar outcomes&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; across repeated trials.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Replicability&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Indicates the ability of researchers to &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;duplicate the study&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; and obtain similar findings.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It ensures that the study&amp;#39;s methods are &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;transparent&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; and reproducible by others.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

questions.statement:
&lt;p&gt;Match the LIST-I with LIST-II&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;table data-path-to-node=&quot;21&quot;&gt;
	&lt;thead&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;LIST-I (Scales of Measurement)&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;LIST-II (Characteristics)&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
	&lt;/thead&gt;
	&lt;tbody&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;A. Nominal&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;I. Place items from least to most or lowest to highest&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;B. Ordinal&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;II. Precisely how far apart the items are&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;C. Ratio&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;III. Denotes the categories only&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;D. Interval&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;IV. Enables researcher to determine the proportions easily&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
	&lt;/tbody&gt;
&lt;/table&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Choose the correct answer from the options given below:&lt;/p&gt;

questions.explanation:
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The correct answer is - &lt;u&gt;A-III, B-I, C-IV, D-II&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt; &lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle; font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;/span&gt; &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Nominal&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Refers to &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;categorical data&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; that represents labels or names to distinguish items.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;No inherent &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;order&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; or ranking is present.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Ordinal&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Used to &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;rank&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; items from least to most or lowest to highest.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Does not specify the &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;exact distance&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; between ranks.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Ratio&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Contains an &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;absolute zero&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;, allowing precise calculations of proportions.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Facilitates determination of &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;ratios&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; between measurements.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Interval&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Measures the &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;distance&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; between values in a consistent scale without an absolute zero.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Allows for comparisons of &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;differences&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; between items.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt; &lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle; font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;/span&gt; &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Scales of Measurement&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Used to classify and measure variables in research and data analysis.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Includes four main types: &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Nominal&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;, &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Ordinal&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;, &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Interval&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;, and &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Ratio&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Characteristics of Measurement Scales&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Nominal&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;: Represents categories without quantitative value.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Ordinal&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;: Indicates order but lacks equal intervals between rankings.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Interval&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;: Provides meaningful differences between measurements but lacks a true zero point.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Ratio&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;: Includes all properties of interval scales plus a true zero point, enabling proportional comparisons.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Applications&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Nominal&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;: Gender, ethnicity, or categories like &amp;quot;pass&amp;quot; and &amp;quot;fail.&amp;quot;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Ordinal&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;: Rankings such as class positions or levels of agreement.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Interval&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;: Temperature scales like Celsius or Fahrenheit.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Ratio&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;: Weight, height, or time measurements.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The correct answer is - &lt;u&gt;Credibility&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt; &lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle; font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;/span&gt; &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Credibility&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; in qualitative research parallels &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;internal validity&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; in quantitative research.

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It ensures the findings of the research are &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;accurate&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;, &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;authentic&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;, and &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;trustworthy&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; from the perspective of the participants.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Credibility is established through techniques like &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;prolonged engagement&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;, &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;persistent observation&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;, and &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;member checking&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It focuses on whether the research reflects the &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;real experiences&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; of participants being studied.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt; &lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle; font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;/span&gt; &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Other criteria in qualitative research&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;:

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Transferability&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;: Refers to how well the findings can be &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;applied&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; to other contexts or settings. It parallels &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;external validity&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Dependability&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;: Focuses on the &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;consistency&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; of research findings over time and parallels &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;reliability&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; in quantitative studies.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Confirmability&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;: Ensures the findings are &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;neutral&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; and free from researcher bias. It parallels &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;objectivity&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Internal validity in quantitative research&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;:
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Refers to the degree to which a study accurately measures what it intends to measure.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;In qualitative research, this is reflected in the &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;credibility&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; of the findings.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

questions.statement:
Arrange the following intervals of standard normal variate in increasing order of probabilities.&lt;br /&gt;
A. 0&amp;le;Z&amp;le;+1&lt;br /&gt;
B. +1&amp;le;Z&amp;lt;+2&lt;br /&gt;
C. +2&amp;le;Z&amp;lt;+3&lt;br /&gt;
D. +3&amp;le;Z&amp;lt;+&amp;infin;&lt;br /&gt;
Choose the correct answer from the options given below:

questions.explanation:
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The correct answer is - &lt;u&gt;D, C, B, A&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt; &lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle; font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;/span&gt; &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Standard normal variate (Z)&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The standard normal distribution is symmetric around the mean (Z = 0), with probabilities assigned to intervals of the distribution.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;As the range of Z-values increases, the probability of occurrence decreases for values further away from the mean.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Interval probabilities&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;u&gt;0 &amp;le; Z &amp;le; +1&lt;/u&gt;: This range has the highest probability because it is closest to the mean.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;u&gt;+1 &amp;le; Z&lt;/u&gt;: Probability decreases compared to the first interval as it includes values further from the mean.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;u&gt;+2 &amp;le; Z&lt;/u&gt;: Probability is even smaller as it represents a smaller tail region of the curve.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;u&gt;+3 &amp;le; Z&lt;/u&gt;: This range has the smallest probability as it represents the extreme tail of the distribution.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Order of probabilities&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;From smallest to largest, the probabilities are in the order: &lt;u&gt;D (&amp;gt;+3 &amp;le; Z)&lt;/u&gt;, &lt;u&gt;C (&amp;gt;+2 &amp;le; Z)&lt;/u&gt;, &lt;u&gt;B (&amp;gt;+1 &amp;le; Z)&lt;/u&gt;, &lt;u&gt;A (0 &amp;le; Z &amp;le; +1)&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt; &lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle; font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;/span&gt; &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Properties of the standard normal distribution&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The standard normal distribution has a mean (&amp;mu;) of 0 and a standard deviation (&amp;sigma;) of 1.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is a symmetric bell-shaped curve, with most data concentrated around the mean.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Approximately 68% of data lies within 1 standard deviation (&amp;plusmn;1&amp;sigma;), 95% within 2 standard deviations (&amp;plusmn;2&amp;sigma;), and 99.7% within 3 standard deviations (&amp;plusmn;3&amp;sigma;).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Probability density function (PDF)&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The PDF of the standard normal distribution is given by:&lt;br /&gt;
		&lt;em&gt;f(Z) = (1/&amp;radic;2&amp;pi;) * e^(-Z&amp;sup2;/2)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The PDF determines the likelihood of Z-values within specific intervals.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

questions.statement:
Identify the advantages of open ended questions in survey research.&lt;br /&gt;
A. It is easy to process answers.&lt;br /&gt;
B. Respondents can answer in their own terms.&lt;br /&gt;
C. They enhance the comparability of answers.&lt;br /&gt;
D. They are useful for exploring new areas or ones in which the researcher has limited knowledge.&lt;br /&gt;
Choose the correct answer from the options given below:

questions.explanation:
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The correct answer is - &lt;u&gt;Respondents can answer in their own terms and they are useful for exploring new areas or ones in which the researcher has limited knowledge&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt; &lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle; font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;/span&gt; &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Respondents can answer in their own terms&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Open-ended questions allow respondents to provide answers that are &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;personalized&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;, detailed, and reflective of their own perspectives.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;These answers are not restricted by predefined options, enabling a broader range of responses.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Useful for exploring new or less-known areas&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Open-ended questions are ideal for collecting data in areas where the researcher has &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;limited prior knowledge&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;They facilitate the discovery of new insights and trends that may not have been anticipated.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt; &lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle; font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;/span&gt; &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Comparability of responses&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Open-ended questions may lack the &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;standardization&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; required for easy comparison of answers across respondents.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;However, they provide rich, qualitative data that can be analyzed for patterns and themes.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Ease of processing&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Responses to open-ended questions are often &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;more time-consuming&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; to process compared to closed-ended questions.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Manual coding or advanced software tools may be required to analyze responses effectively.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

questions.statement:
Mean and variance for four different Binomial distributions with parameters n (number of trials) and p (probability of success) are given in A-D below. Compute the number of trials (n) for each&lt;br /&gt;
Binomial distribution and arrange in ascending order.&lt;br /&gt;
A. Mean = 2.1, Variance = 1.47&lt;br /&gt;
B. Mean = 2.0, Variance = 1.20&lt;br /&gt;
C. Mean = 4.0, Variance = 2.00&lt;br /&gt;
D. Mean = 3.6, Variance = 1.44&lt;br /&gt;
Choose the correct answer from the options given below:

questions.explanation:
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The correct answer is - &lt;u&gt;B, D, A, C&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt; &lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle; font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;/span&gt; &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Binomial distribution&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; is characterized by two parameters:

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Mean (&amp;mu;)&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; = &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;n &amp;times; p&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;, where &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;n&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; is the number of trials, and &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;p&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; is the probability of success.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Variance (&amp;sigma;&amp;sup2;)&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; = &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;n &amp;times; p &amp;times; (1 - p)&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;To find &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;n&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;, use the formula:
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;p&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; = &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Mean / Variance&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Substitute &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;p&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; into &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;n = Mean / p&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; to compute &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;n&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Using the given values:
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;A:&lt;/strong&gt; Mean = 2.1, Variance = 1.47&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;B:&lt;/strong&gt; Mean = 2.0, Variance = 1.20&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;C:&lt;/strong&gt; Mean = 4.0, Variance = 2.00&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;D:&lt;/strong&gt; Mean = 3.6, Variance = 1.44&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Calculate &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;n&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; for each:
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;B:&lt;/strong&gt; p = 2.0 / 1.20 = 0.6, n = 2.0 / 0.6 = 3.33 (approx).&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;D:&lt;/strong&gt; p = 3.6 / 1.44 = 0.4, n = 3.6 / 0.4 = 9.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;A:&lt;/strong&gt; p = 2.1 / 1.47 = 0.428, n = 2.1 / 0.428 = 4.91 (approx).&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;C:&lt;/strong&gt; p = 4.0 / 2.00 = 0.5, n = 4.0 / 0.5 = 8.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Arrange &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;n&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; in ascending order: &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;B, D, A, C&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt; &lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle; font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;/span&gt; &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Binomial Distribution&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; properties:

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It applies to scenarios with a fixed number of &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;independent trials&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Each trial has only two outcomes: &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;success&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; or &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;failure&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The probability &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;p&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; of success remains constant across trials.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Mean and Variance Relationship&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;:
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The mean is directly proportional to both &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;n&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; and &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;p&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Variance depends on both the probability of success (&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;p&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;) and failure (&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;1 - p&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Applications of Binomial Distribution&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;:
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Used in scenarios like coin tosses, quality control, and medical trials.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Helps in estimating probabilities in binary outcomes.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

questions.statement:
&lt;p data-path-to-node=&quot;0&quot;&gt;Match List-I with List-II:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;table data-path-to-node=&quot;1&quot;&gt;
	&lt;thead&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;td style=&quot;text-align: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;List-I (Research Study)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td style=&quot;text-align: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;List-II (Research Method)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
	&lt;/thead&gt;
	&lt;tbody&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;A. Peer interaction in a mixed-race classroom of an urban high school&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;I. Cross-sectional Survey Research&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;B. Developmental pattern of intelligence among secondary level school students&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;II. Ex-Post Facto Research&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;C. Effect of television viewing on the science achievement of 9th-grade students&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;III. Ethnographic Research&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;D. Impact of education on the social status of marginal groups&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;IV. Experimental Research&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
	&lt;/tbody&gt;
&lt;/table&gt;

questions.explanation:
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The correct answer is &amp;ndash; &lt;u&gt;A-III, B-I, C-IV, D-II&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt; &lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle; font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;/span&gt; &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;A. Peer interaction in a mixed-race classroom&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;This involves studying &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;natural social interactions&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; within a specific cultural group.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The researcher observes behaviour in a &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;real-life setting&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; without manipulation.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Hence, it is best studied using &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Ethnographic Research&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;So, &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;A &amp;rarr; III&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;B. Developmental pattern of intelligence&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;This focuses on differences in intelligence across students at a given stage.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Data are collected from a &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;defined population at one point in time&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;This corresponds to &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Cross-sectional Survey Research&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;So, &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;B &amp;rarr; I&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;C. Effect of television viewing on achievement&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Examines a &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;cause&amp;ndash;effect relationship&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; between exposure and achievement.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Requires &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;manipulation of an independent variable&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; (TV viewing).&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;This is characteristic of &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Experimental Research&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;So, &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;C &amp;rarr; IV&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;D. Impact of education on social status&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The cause (education) has already occurred and cannot be manipulated.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The researcher studies its &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;after-effects&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; on social status.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;This defines &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Ex-Post Facto Research&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;So, &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;D &amp;rarr; II&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt; &lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle; font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;/span&gt; &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Ethnographic Research&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Emphasizes &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;participant observation&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; and cultural interpretation.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Experimental Research&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Involves &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;control and manipulation&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; of variables to establish causality.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Ex-Post Facto Research&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Used when variables cannot be controlled for ethical or practical reasons.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Cross-sectional Survey&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Provides a snapshot of characteristics across a population at one time.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

questions.statement:
Identify the correct sequence of steps in the process of deduction from the following:&lt;br /&gt;
A. Data Collection&lt;br /&gt;
B. Hypothesis Testing&lt;br /&gt;
C. Theory&lt;br /&gt;
D. Findings&lt;br /&gt;
E. Hypothesis Formulation&lt;br /&gt;
Choose the correct answer from the options given below :

questions.explanation:
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The correct answer is - &lt;u&gt;Theory, Hypothesis Formulation, Data Collection, Findings, Hypothesis Testing&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt; &lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle; font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;/span&gt; &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;The correct sequence&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; in the process of deduction follows a logical order:

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Theory&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;: The starting point, where a general principle or framework is established.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Hypothesis Formulation&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;: A specific, testable prediction is derived from the theory.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Data Collection&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;: Relevant data is gathered to test the hypothesis.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Findings&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;: The results of the data analysis are evaluated.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Hypothesis Testing&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;: The hypothesis is verified or falsified based on the findings.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Deductive reasoning&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; starts with a general theory and works down to specific conclusions.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt; &lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle; font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;/span&gt; &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Theory&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;:

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;A theory is a well-established principle developed to explain phenomena.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It serves as the foundation for formulating hypotheses.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Hypothesis Formulation&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;:
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;A hypothesis is a specific, testable prediction derived from a theory.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is framed to address the research question or problem.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Data Collection&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;:
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Gathering relevant and reliable data is crucial for hypothesis testing.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Methods include surveys, experiments, observations, etc.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Findings&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;:
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Findings represent the analysis of the collected data.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;They help determine whether the hypothesis is supported or refuted.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Hypothesis Testing&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;:
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;This is the final step in the deductive process.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It involves evaluating whether the findings align with the hypothesis and theory.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

questions.statement:
Population standard deviation (&amp;sigma;) and&amp;nbsp;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(\frac{1}{N}\sum x_i^2\)&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;(xᵢ &amp;gt; 0) of different datasets are given in A-D below. Compute the population mean of each dataset and arrange in descending order.&lt;br /&gt;
A. &amp;sigma; = 5,&amp;nbsp;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(\frac{1}{N}\sum x_i^2 = 61\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
B. &amp;sigma; = 7,&amp;nbsp;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(\frac{1}{N}\sum x_i^2 = 113\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
C. &amp;sigma; = 8,&amp;nbsp;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(\frac{1}{N}\sum x_i^2 = 145\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
D. &amp;sigma; = 6,&amp;nbsp;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(\frac{1}{N}\sum x_i^2 = 85\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
Choose the correct answer from the options given below:

questions.explanation:
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The correct answer is - &lt;u&gt;C, B, D, A&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt; &lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle; font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;/span&gt; &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Population mean calculation formula&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;:

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The formula for population variance is: &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;&amp;sigma;&amp;sup2; = [ (1/N) &amp;Sigma;xᵢ&amp;sup2; ] - &amp;mu;&amp;sup2;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;, where:

		&lt;ul&gt;
			&lt;li&gt;&amp;sigma; = Population standard deviation&lt;/li&gt;
			&lt;li&gt;&amp;mu; = Population mean&lt;/li&gt;
			&lt;li&gt;(1/N) &amp;Sigma;xᵢ&amp;sup2; = Mean of squares of data points&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;/ul&gt;
		&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Rearranging the formula gives: &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;&amp;mu;&amp;sup2; = [ (1/N) &amp;Sigma;xᵢ&amp;sup2; ] - &amp;sigma;&amp;sup2;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Taking the square root gives: &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;&amp;mu; = &amp;radic;{ [ (1/N) &amp;Sigma;xᵢ&amp;sup2; ] - &amp;sigma;&amp;sup2; }&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Step-by-step calculations&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; for datasets A, B, C, and D:
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;For A:&lt;/strong&gt;
		&lt;ul&gt;
			&lt;li&gt;&amp;sigma; = 5, (1/N) &amp;Sigma;xᵢ&amp;sup2; = 61&lt;/li&gt;
			&lt;li&gt;&amp;mu;&amp;sup2; = 61 - (5&amp;sup2;) = 61 - 25 = 36&lt;/li&gt;
			&lt;li&gt;&amp;mu; = &amp;radic;36 = 6&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;/ul&gt;
		&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;For B:&lt;/strong&gt;
		&lt;ul&gt;
			&lt;li&gt;&amp;sigma; = 7, (1/N) &amp;Sigma;xᵢ&amp;sup2; = 113&lt;/li&gt;
			&lt;li&gt;&amp;mu;&amp;sup2; = 113 - (7&amp;sup2;) = 113 - 49 = 64&lt;/li&gt;
			&lt;li&gt;&amp;mu; = &amp;radic;64 = 8&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;/ul&gt;
		&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;For C:&lt;/strong&gt;
		&lt;ul&gt;
			&lt;li&gt;&amp;sigma; = 8, (1/N) &amp;Sigma;xᵢ&amp;sup2; = 145&lt;/li&gt;
			&lt;li&gt;&amp;mu;&amp;sup2; = 145 - (8&amp;sup2;) = 145 - 64 = 81&lt;/li&gt;
			&lt;li&gt;&amp;mu; = &amp;radic;81 = 9&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;/ul&gt;
		&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;For D:&lt;/strong&gt;
		&lt;ul&gt;
			&lt;li&gt;&amp;sigma; = 6, (1/N) &amp;Sigma;xᵢ&amp;sup2; = 85&lt;/li&gt;
			&lt;li&gt;&amp;mu;&amp;sup2; = 85 - (6&amp;sup2;) = 85 - 36 = 49&lt;/li&gt;
			&lt;li&gt;&amp;mu; = &amp;radic;49 = 7&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;/ul&gt;
		&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Descending order&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; of population means: &lt;strong&gt;C (9), B (8), D (7), A (6)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt; &lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle; font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;/span&gt; &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Population variance and standard deviation&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;:

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Population variance measures the average squared deviation of each data point from the mean.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Population standard deviation (&amp;sigma;) is the square root of the variance.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It represents the spread or dispersion of the dataset.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Mean of squares (1/N &amp;Sigma;xᵢ&amp;sup2;)&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;:
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;This term refers to the average of the squares of all data points in the dataset.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is used in the formula to calculate the variance and mean.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key distinction between population and sample metrics&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;:
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The formulas for population and sample variance differ slightly. For a population, N is used, while for a sample, (N-1) is used in the denominator to account for degrees of freedom.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

questions.statement:
Match List - I with List - II.
&lt;table data-path-to-node=&quot;12&quot;&gt;
	&lt;thead&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;List - I (Measurement Scale)&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;List - II (Appropriate Example)&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
	&lt;/thead&gt;
	&lt;tbody&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;A. Ordinal&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;I. Color of Hair&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;B. Ratio&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;II. Satisfaction Level&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;C. Nominal&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;III. Difference in temperature in degree Celsius&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;D. Interval&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;IV. Salary of employees&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
	&lt;/tbody&gt;
&lt;/table&gt;
Choose the correct answer from the options given below :

questions.explanation:
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The correct answer is - &lt;u&gt;A-II, B-IV, C-I, D-III&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt; &lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle; font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;/span&gt; &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Ordinal Scale&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;An &lt;u&gt;ordinal scale&lt;/u&gt; ranks or orders data but does not quantify the differences between ranks.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;u&gt;Satisfaction Level&lt;/u&gt; is an example because it can be ranked (e.g., very satisfied, satisfied, neutral, dissatisfied), but the difference between ranks is not measurable.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Ratio Scale&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The &lt;u&gt;ratio scale&lt;/u&gt; has a true zero and allows for comparison of absolute magnitudes.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;u&gt;Salary of employees&lt;/u&gt; is an example because it has a true zero point and comparisons such as &amp;ldquo;twice as much&amp;rdquo; can be made.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Nominal Scale&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The &lt;u&gt;nominal scale&lt;/u&gt; categorizes data without any order or ranking.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;u&gt;Color of hair&lt;/u&gt; is an example because it represents categories (e.g., black, brown, blonde) without any inherent order.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Interval Scale&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The &lt;u&gt;interval scale&lt;/u&gt; measures differences between values but lacks a true zero point.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;u&gt;Difference in temperature in degree Celsius&lt;/u&gt; is an example because it measures intervals between values, but zero degrees Celsius does not represent the absence of temperature.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt; &lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle; font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;/span&gt; &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Measurement Scales&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;u&gt;Nominal&lt;/u&gt;: Used for labeling variables without any quantitative value.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;u&gt;Ordinal&lt;/u&gt;: Allows for ranking or ordering of variables but does not measure the magnitude of differences.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;u&gt;Interval&lt;/u&gt;: Measures differences between values with equal intervals but lacks a true zero point.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;u&gt;Ratio&lt;/u&gt;: Similar to interval but includes a true zero, allowing for meaningful comparisons of absolute quantities.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Examples of Usage&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Nominal: Gender, color, types of fruits.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Ordinal: Customer satisfaction, ranks in a competition.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Interval: Temperature, time on a clock.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Ratio: Height, weight, age, salary.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The correct answer is - &lt;u&gt;Quantitative research&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt; &lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle; font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;/span&gt; &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Measurement validity&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; refers to the extent to which a measurement instrument accurately captures the concept it is intended to measure.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It is primarily associated with &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Quantitative research&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;, which relies on numerical data and statistical methods.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In quantitative research, ensuring measurement validity is critical for:
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Reliability&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;: Consistency of results across repeated measurements.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Accuracy&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;: Correct representation of the concept being studied.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Examples of measurement validity include:
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Using standardized tests to measure intelligence.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Ensuring survey questions directly align with research objectives.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt; &lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle; font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;/span&gt; &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Types of Validity&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; in quantitative research:

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Construct validity&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;: Ensures the measurement truly represents the concept it is meant to measure.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Content validity&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;: Ensures all aspects of the concept are adequately covered by the measurement tool.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Criterion validity&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;: Compares the measurement to external criteria to verify accuracy.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key differences&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; between qualitative and quantitative research:
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Quantitative research&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; focuses on measurable data and statistical methods, while &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;qualitative research&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; emphasizes subjective understanding and interpretation.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Measurement validity is less emphasized in qualitative research, where concepts like credibility and trustworthiness are prioritized.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Importance of validity&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;:
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Ensures the research findings are trustworthy and applicable.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Improves the reliability and usability of results for decision-making and further studies.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

questions.statement:
Arrange the following pairs of standard deviation (&amp;sigma;) and total number of samples (n) pertaining to different sampling distributions in the decreasing order of their standard error.&lt;br /&gt;
A. &amp;sigma;=1.6, n=16&lt;br /&gt;
B. &amp;sigma;=1.5, n = 25&lt;br /&gt;
C. &amp;sigma;=0.6, n=36&lt;br /&gt;
D. &amp;sigma;=1.4, n = 49&lt;br /&gt;
Choose the correct answer from the options given below :

questions.explanation:
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The correct answer is - &lt;u&gt;A, B, D, C&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt; &lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle; font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;/span&gt; &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;standard error&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; (SE) of a sampling distribution is calculated using the formula:

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;SE = &amp;sigma; / &amp;radic;n&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;, where:

		&lt;ul&gt;
			&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;&amp;sigma;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; is the standard deviation.&lt;/li&gt;
			&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;n&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; is the total number of samples.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;/ul&gt;
		&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;larger the SE&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;, the higher the variability in the sampling distribution.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Now, calculating SE for each pair:
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;For A (&amp;sigma; = 1.6, n = 16): SE = 1.6 / &amp;radic;16 = 1.6 / 4 = &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;0.4&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;For B (&amp;sigma; = 1.5, n = 25): SE = 1.5 / &amp;radic;25 = 1.5 / 5 = &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;0.3&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;For C (&amp;sigma; = 0.6, n = 36): SE = 0.6 / &amp;radic;36 = 0.6 / 6 = &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;0.1&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;For D (&amp;sigma; = 1.4, n = 49): SE = 1.4 / &amp;radic;49 = 1.4 / 7 = &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;0.2&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Arranging the SE values in decreasing order: &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;0.4 (A), 0.3 (B), 0.2 (D), 0.1 (C)&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt; &lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle; font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;/span&gt; &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Standard Error (SE)&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;:

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;standard error&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; quantifies how much the sample mean differs from the population mean.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It decreases as the sample size (&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;n&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;) increases, as larger samples reduce variability.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Relationship between SE and &amp;sigma;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;:
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;A larger standard deviation (&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;&amp;sigma;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;) increases the SE, indicating higher variability in the sampling distribution.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Practical Implication&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;:
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;In experiments and surveys, reducing the SE by increasing the sample size can improve the accuracy of population estimates.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The correct answer is - &lt;u&gt;6&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt; &lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle; font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;/span&gt; &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;H-index&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;h-index&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; is a measure of the cumulative impact of a researcher&amp;#39;s publications. It is determined by the number of papers (h) that have been cited at least h times.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Calculation of Dr. Amit&amp;#39;s h-index&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The citation counts for Dr. Amit&amp;#39;s papers are: 9, 7, 3, 11, 4, 8, 2, 12, 6, and 1.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Sort the citation counts in descending order: 12, 11, 9, 8, 7, 6, 4, 3, 2, 1.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Identify the largest number &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;h&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; such that at least &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;h&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; papers have been cited &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;h&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; times:
		&lt;ul&gt;
			&lt;li&gt;1st paper: 12 citations (&amp;ge; 1)&lt;/li&gt;
			&lt;li&gt;2nd paper: 11 citations (&amp;ge; 2)&lt;/li&gt;
			&lt;li&gt;3rd paper: 9 citations (&amp;ge; 3)&lt;/li&gt;
			&lt;li&gt;4th paper: 8 citations (&amp;ge; 4)&lt;/li&gt;
			&lt;li&gt;5th paper: 7 citations (&amp;ge; 5)&lt;/li&gt;
			&lt;li&gt;6th paper: 6 citations (&amp;ge; 6)&lt;/li&gt;
			&lt;li&gt;7th paper: 4 citations (&amp;lt; 7) &amp;ndash; Stop here.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;/ul&gt;
		&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The h-index is &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;6&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;, as 6 papers have at least 6 citations each.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt; &lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle; font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;/span&gt; &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Significance of the h-index&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;h-index&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; balances the quantity and quality of a researcher&amp;#39;s work by combining productivity (number of papers) with impact (number of citations).&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;A higher h-index indicates a stronger influence in the research field.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Limitations of the h-index&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It does not account for highly cited papers beyond the h-index threshold.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It may vary across disciplines due to differing citation practices.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It does not consider the timing of citations or the author&amp;#39;s contribution to multi-author papers.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Alternative Metrics&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;i10-index&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;: The number of papers with at least 10 citations.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;g-index&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;: Gives more weight to highly-cited papers compared to the h-index.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Altmetrics&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;: Measures the broader impact of research using social media, news, and other platforms.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

questions.statement:
Given below are two statements: one is labelled as Assertion A and the other is labelled as Reason R&lt;br /&gt;
Assertion A: Online survey tools have made the surveying and data analysis easier.&lt;br /&gt;
Reason R: Online surveys do not present challenges like selection bias.&lt;br /&gt;
In the light of the above statements, choose the most appropriate answer from the options given below

questions.explanation:
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The correct answer is - &lt;u&gt;A is correct but R is not correct&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt; &lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle; font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;/span&gt; &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Assertion A&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; is correct because:

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Online survey tools have significantly streamlined the process of conducting surveys by automating data collection and analysis.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;These tools allow for faster data processing, real-time results, and easier access to a larger audience.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Features like pre-designed templates, analytics dashboards, and data visualization make surveys more efficient.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Reason R&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; is incorrect because:
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Online surveys are prone to &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;selection bias&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;, as not all participants may have equal access to the internet or the devices needed to participate.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Demographic representation may be skewed, leading to unbalanced datasets.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Other issues like low response rates and self-selection bias can also impact the validity of the data collected.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt; &lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle; font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;/span&gt; &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Selection Bias&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Occurs when certain groups in the population are underrepresented or overrepresented in the sample data.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It can lead to inaccurate conclusions and affects the generalizability of survey results.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Advantages of Online Surveys&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Cost-effective compared to traditional paper-based surveys.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Greater reach, allowing for global participation.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Eco-friendly, reducing the need for physical resources like paper and printing.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Challenges with Online Surveys&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Dependence on technology may exclude participants without internet access or technical knowledge.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Risk of low response rates, as participants may ignore online survey invitations.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

questions.statement:
As a Junior Research Fellow (JRF), you plagiarized someone&amp;#39;s work and you are caught, what is the likely consequence ?&lt;br /&gt;
A. You will be rewarded for that over time.&lt;br /&gt;
B. The research article is retracted with public documentation explaining the reason.&lt;br /&gt;
C. The institute funding your research takes disciplinary action.&lt;br /&gt;
D. Your academic standing and reputation come into question.&lt;br /&gt;
Choose the correct answer from the options given below:

questions.explanation:
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The correct answer is - &lt;u&gt;The research article is retracted with public documentation explaining the reason and your academic standing and reputation come into question&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt; &lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle; font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;/span&gt; &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Plagiarism consequences in academic research&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;If plagiarism is detected, the &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;research article is retracted&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;, and the reason is documented publicly to maintain academic integrity.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Your &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;academic reputation&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; and standing are impacted negatively, leading to potential loss of credibility in the research community.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Public documentation&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Retraction notices explain the reason, ensuring transparency and accountability in scientific publishing.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Impact on career&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Such incidents can lead to &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;disciplinary actions&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; from the institute or funding body and hinder future academic opportunities.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt; &lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle; font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;/span&gt; &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Plagiarism detection and tools&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Institutes and publishers use advanced tools like &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Turnitin&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; and &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;iThenticate&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; to identify plagiarism in research work.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Ethical guidelines&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Researchers are required to adhere to &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;ethical standards&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;, such as proper citation and originality, as outlined by organizations like &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;COPE (Committee on Publication Ethics)&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Preventing plagiarism&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Proper citation practices and the use of plagiarism-prevention tools can help researchers avoid ethical violations.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Institutes often conduct &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;training sessions&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; to educate researchers about maintaining academic integrity.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

questions.statement:
Quantitative research can be characterised as exhibiting certain preoccupations the most central of which are:&lt;br /&gt;
A. Causality&lt;br /&gt;
B. Replication&lt;br /&gt;
C. Generalisation&lt;br /&gt;
D. Measurement&lt;br /&gt;
Choose the correct answer from the options given below:

questions.explanation:
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The correct answer is - &lt;u&gt;A, B, C and D&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt; &lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle; font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;/span&gt; &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Quantitative research&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is primarily concerned with exploring relationships between variables and examining &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;causality&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;. This helps in understanding how one variable affects another.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Replication&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; is a core aspect, as it ensures that findings are valid and reliable by allowing others to duplicate the study under similar conditions.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Generalisation&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; is achieved by studying a sample that represents a larger population, making the results applicable to broader contexts.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Measurement&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; is crucial for gathering numerical data and performing statistical analysis, which forms the backbone of quantitative research.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt; &lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle; font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;/span&gt; &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key features of quantitative research&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Uses structured tools like surveys, experiments, and standardized tests to collect data.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Relies on numerical data, which is often analyzed using statistical methods for accuracy and precision.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Aims to test hypotheses and establish patterns or trends within a population.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Applications of quantitative research&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Widely used in fields like social sciences, psychology, education, and business to derive actionable insights.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Helps in making evidence-based decisions by providing objective and measurable results.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The correct answer is - &lt;u&gt;Internal validity&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt; &lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle; font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;/span&gt; &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Internal validity&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Refers to the &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;accuracy&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; of a study&amp;#39;s conclusions regarding the relationship between the independent variable (&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;x&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;) and the dependent variable (&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;y&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;).&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Ensures that the observed effect on the dependent variable is due to the manipulation of the independent variable and not due to &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;confounding factors&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;High &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;internal validity&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; is essential for establishing &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;causal relationships&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; in experimental research.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;To achieve this, researchers must control for potential &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;confounding variables&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; and use proper experimental designs.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt; &lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle; font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;/span&gt; &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;External validity&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Refers to the &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;generalizability&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; of findings to other populations, settings, or times.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is unrelated to causation but evaluates whether the results can be applied beyond the study&amp;#39;s scope.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Reliability&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Measures the &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;consistency&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; or &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;repeatability&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; of results across trials or experiments.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Reliability does not evaluate causation, but ensures data precision and accuracy.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Ecological validity&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Refers to the extent to which findings can be applied to &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;real-world settings&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is focused on the realism of the experimental conditions rather than causal relationships.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

questions.statement:
&lt;p&gt;Match List - I with List - II.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;table border=&quot;1&quot; cellpadding=&quot;1&quot; cellspacing=&quot;1&quot; style=&quot;width:100%;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;tbody&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;List - I&amp;nbsp;Mixed Method Design&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;List - II&amp;nbsp;Nature&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;A. QUAN &amp;rarr;&amp;nbsp;qual&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;I. Exploratory sequential design&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;B. &lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/images/production/quesImages/qImage69787f3a5089cf1ceb53ecad.png&quot; /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;II. Explanatory sequential design&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;C. QUAL &amp;rarr; quan&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;III. Embedded design&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;D. QUAN + QUAL&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;IV. Convergent parallel design&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
	&lt;/tbody&gt;
&lt;/table&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Choose the correct answer from the options given below:&lt;/p&gt;

questions.explanation:
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;The correct answer is &amp;ndash; A-II, B-III, C-I, D-IV&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt; &lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle; font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;/span&gt; &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Mixed Method Research Design&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Mixed method designs combine &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;quantitative (QUAN)&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; and &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;qualitative (QUAL)&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; approaches.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The notation indicates the &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;sequence&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; and &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;priority&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; of methods.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Correct Matching Explanation&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;A: QUAN &amp;rarr; qual&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;
		&lt;ul&gt;
			&lt;li&gt;Quantitative data is collected first, followed by qualitative data.&lt;/li&gt;
			&lt;li&gt;Qualitative phase helps explain quantitative findings.&lt;/li&gt;
			&lt;li&gt;This corresponds to &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Explanatory sequential design&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
			&lt;li&gt;Hence, &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;A &amp;rarr; II&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;/ul&gt;
		&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;B: QUAL (embedded) quan&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;
		&lt;ul&gt;
			&lt;li&gt;One method plays a &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;supportive role&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; within another dominant method.&lt;/li&gt;
			&lt;li&gt;Qualitative data is embedded within a quantitative framework.&lt;/li&gt;
			&lt;li&gt;This structure represents an &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Embedded design&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
			&lt;li&gt;Hence, &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;B &amp;rarr; III&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;/ul&gt;
		&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;C: QUAL &amp;rarr; quan&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;
		&lt;ul&gt;
			&lt;li&gt;Qualitative exploration is conducted first.&lt;/li&gt;
			&lt;li&gt;Findings are used to develop instruments or hypotheses for quantitative study.&lt;/li&gt;
			&lt;li&gt;This sequence defines an &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Exploratory sequential design&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
			&lt;li&gt;Hence, &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;C &amp;rarr; I&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;/ul&gt;
		&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;D: QUAN + QUAL&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;
		&lt;ul&gt;
			&lt;li&gt;Both quantitative and qualitative data are collected &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;simultaneously&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
			&lt;li&gt;Equal priority is given to both methods.&lt;/li&gt;
			&lt;li&gt;This represents a &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Convergent parallel design&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
			&lt;li&gt;Hence, &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;D &amp;rarr; IV&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: none;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;/ul&gt;
		&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt; &lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle; font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;/span&gt; &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Sequential Designs&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Data collection occurs in &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;distinct phases&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Later phase is informed by results of the earlier phase.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Parallel Designs&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Both methods are implemented at the &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;same time&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Results are compared or merged during interpretation.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The correct answer is - &lt;u&gt;Comparative design&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt; &lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle; font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;/span&gt; &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Comparative design&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;This research design involves &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;studying two contrasting cases&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; using more or less &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;identical methods&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It aims to highlight &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;differences&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; or &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;similarities&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; between the cases to provide deeper insights into the phenomena being studied.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Comparative designs are widely used in the fields of &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;social sciences&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;, &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;politics&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;, and &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;economics&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;This method helps in understanding how variables behave across different contexts.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt; &lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle; font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;/span&gt; &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Experimental design&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Focuses on &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;manipulating variables&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; to test causal relationships.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Often used in controlled environments to ensure &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;accuracy and reliability&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Longitudinal design&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Involves studying the same subjects over a &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;long period of time&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Effective for observing trends or changes in &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;behavior&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; or &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;phenomena&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Latitudinal design&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Not commonly used or recognized as a formal research design.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;May refer to studies conducted across &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;geographical regions&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;, but lacks specificity in research methodology.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The correct answer is - &lt;u&gt;The probability of observing results as extreme or more extreme than currently observed, given that the null hypothesis is true&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt; &lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle; font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;/span&gt; &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;P-value&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;p-value&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; quantifies the probability of obtaining results as extreme as the observed data, assuming the &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;null hypothesis&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; is true.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is a measure of evidence against the null hypothesis.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;A smaller &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;p-value&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; indicates stronger evidence to reject the null hypothesis.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Statistical significance&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;If the &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;p-value&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; is less than the chosen significance level (e.g., 0.05), the results are considered statistically significant.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Statistical significance suggests that the observed results are unlikely to have occurred by chance under the null hypothesis.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt; &lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle; font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;/span&gt; &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Null Hypothesis (H₀)&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;null hypothesis&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; is a statement that there is no effect or no difference in the population.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It serves as the default assumption in statistical hypothesis testing.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Alternative Hypothesis (H₁)&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;alternative hypothesis&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; states that there is an effect or a difference in the population.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Rejecting the null hypothesis supports the alternative hypothesis.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Significance Level (&amp;alpha;)&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;significance level&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; is the threshold probability used to determine whether the p-value indicates statistical significance.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Commonly used values for &amp;alpha; include 0.05, 0.01, or 0.10.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Interpretation of p-value&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;A &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;high p-value&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; (&amp;gt; &amp;alpha;) suggests weak evidence against the null hypothesis, so it is not rejected.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;A &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;low p-value&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; (&amp;lt; &amp;alpha;) suggests strong evidence against the null hypothesis, leading to rejection.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

questions.statement:
Match List - I with List - II.
&lt;table&gt;
	&lt;tbody&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;&lt;b&gt;List - I&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;&lt;b&gt;List - II&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;A. Independent variable in true experimental design&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;I. Outcome variable&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;B. Dependent variable&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;II. Control variable&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;C. Intervening variable&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;III. Spurious variable&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;D. Confounding variable&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;IV. Stands between independent variable and dependent variable&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
	&lt;/tbody&gt;
&lt;/table&gt;
Choose the correct answer from the options given below:

questions.explanation:
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The correct answer is - &lt;u&gt;A-II, B-I, C-IV, D-III&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt; &lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle; font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;/span&gt; &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Independent Variable&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;In a &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;true experimental design&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;, the independent variable is the one that is &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;manipulated&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; by the researcher to observe its effect on the dependent variable.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is matched with &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;II (Control variable)&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; in the question.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Dependent Variable&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The dependent variable is the &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;outcome variable&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;, which changes as a result of manipulations in the independent variable.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is correctly matched with &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;I (Outcome variable)&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Intervening Variable&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;An intervening variable is one that &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;stands between the independent and dependent variables&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;, potentially affecting the relationship between the two.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is correctly matched with &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;IV&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Confounding Variable&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;A confounding variable is one that is &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;spurious&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;, potentially creating a false impression of a relationship between the independent and dependent variables.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is matched with &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;III&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt; &lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle; font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;/span&gt; &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Experimental Design Components&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Independent Variable:&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; The variable manipulated by the researcher.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Dependent Variable:&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; The variable measured to assess the impact of changes in the independent variable.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Control Variables:&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; Variables kept constant to ensure that any observed effects are due to the independent variable.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Confounding Variables:&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; Uncontrolled variables that can affect the results and lead to erroneous conclusions.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Intervening Variables&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;These variables are internal processes that may mediate the relationship between the independent and dependent variables.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;For example, in a study of teaching methods (independent variable) and student performance (dependent variable), factors like motivation could act as intervening variables.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Confounding Variables&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Confounding variables can distort the true relationship between the independent and dependent variables by introducing bias.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Researchers often use randomization or statistical controls to minimize the influence of confounding variables.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

questions.statement:
Identify the advantages of closed ended questions in survey research:&lt;br /&gt;
A. It is easy to process answers.&lt;br /&gt;
B. Respondents can answer in their own terms.&lt;br /&gt;
C. They are easy for the respondents to complete.&lt;br /&gt;
D. They allow unusual responses to be derived.&lt;br /&gt;
Choose the correct answer from the options given below :

questions.explanation:
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The correct answer is - &lt;u&gt;A and C only&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt; &lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle; font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;/span&gt; &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Closed-ended questions&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;They provide pre-defined response options, making it &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;easier to process answers&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;. This allows the researcher to categorize and analyze data more efficiently.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Such questions are &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;simple for respondents to answer&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;, as they involve selecting from given choices rather than crafting detailed responses.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Why A and C are correct&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;u&gt;Statement A&lt;/u&gt;: Closed-ended questions simplify the data processing as the responses are uniform and standardized.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;u&gt;Statement C&lt;/u&gt;: Since respondents only need to select an option, completing the survey is easier and less time-consuming.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt; &lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle; font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;/span&gt; &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Why B and D are incorrect&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;u&gt;Statement B&lt;/u&gt;: Closed-ended questions do not allow respondents to answer in their own terms. Instead, they restrict responses to the given options.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;u&gt;Statement D&lt;/u&gt;: Such questions do not capture unusual or unexpected responses, as they limit the scope of answers to pre-defined choices.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Advantages of closed-ended questions&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;They are particularly useful in large-scale surveys where &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;quantitative data&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; is needed.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Pre-defined options reduce the risk of variability in responses, ensuring &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;consistency&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; and easier comparison across respondents.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;These questions are less prone to interviewer bias during data collection.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Limitations of closed-ended questions&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;They may not capture the &lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;depth of respondents&amp;#39; opinions&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;, as the answers are restricted to given choices.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Closed-ended questions can sometimes force respondents to choose an option that may not fully represent their true opinion.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

